description: From Mediaeval Latin incastellātus (“fortified, incastled, incastellate”), from in- (“in-: make into”) + castellum (“little fortification, castle”). Equivalent to incastle + -ate and cognate with Italian incastellare.

verbs.description: incastellate (third-person singular simple present incastellates, present participle incastellating, simple past and past participle incastellated)

entries.meaning: (transitive, obsolete) To make into a castle.

verbs.description: incastellate (third-person singular simple present incastellates, present participle incastellating, simple past and past participle incastellated)
